They only have to land it once, and most rogues don't even bother using it on casters because they can drop you in less than 10 seconds just with a few melee hits and a double backstab.<br>
<br>
Ranger-/disc trueshot + primal bow<br>
You ever get tagged for 400 a shot from someone who is running faster than you and tracking you?   It's a lot of fun.<br>
<br>
Shadowknight-/disc death touch  <br>
They double you one time with a primal axe for 304 a pop and then drop you with HT disc.  Or if they get bored they can just kill you using lifetaps.<br>
<br>
Warrior-Tantors Tusk/primal axe<br>
It's pretty simple, they beat you to death in any confined space and most likely outdoors to with a couple of lucky swings.  <br>
<br>
Monks-Tranquil Staff proc + /disc inner fire<br>
Monks are evil, if tranq staff procs on you you're toast. Even if tranq staff doesn't proc they can still beat you to death with a speed that will blow your mind.<br>
<br>
Paladins- Energizer Bunnies<br>
A well played paladin is the hardest class to kill bar none.  Primal axe HURTS casters.<br>
<br>
Bards-pet charm<br>
They aren't really dangerous in pvp if they don't use their pet charm exploit.  They really don't have a great deal of damage output even when they have primal + epic.<br>
<br>
Enchanters- Rapture /bye<br>
Rapture, mana drain, mez pet, kill you at their leisure.  Er, actually of the pure casters enchanters are the second easiest to smoke.<br>
<br>
Magician- Banishment and blow them away.<br>
Velocity is your friend.<br>
<br>
Necromancer-gay lifetaps<br>
use insta cast pumice on their dots and they'll run out of mana pretty quickly and be forced to run.  Valiant companion is always nice to prevent them from doing what they like most, which is fearing pets into mobs.<br>
<br>
Wizard-not going into it anymore.<br>
<br>
Cleric- root/fear/blind.<br>
Smart clerics will keep your pet out of the picture and melee you to death........I'm not kidding btw.<br>
<br>
Druid-dots/nukes/heals<br>
pumice their dots. you're biggest problem hear is that they have more hp than you, nuke just as well, and they can run around regenning hp like crazy with a fungal tunic and regrowth.  Use golem wands on these people.<br>
<br>
Shaman-Give up<br>
If you're fighting a well played shaman you don't really stand much of a chance.  No easy way I can break it to you.  He'll spam that epic over and over while he kites your pet around before coming back for you.  Not too mention that he'll put your dr through the floor and give you the disease line of spells.  Right click sow boots are nasty.  Oh yeah, forgot to mention that most shamans will try and beat you death to with melee.<br>
<br>
These situations are all competent level 60 vs competent level 60.   It's really hard to convince people who haven't seen it on a regular basis.  I'm not saying you'll lose everytime, I'm just reminding you that you're not all getting your info from diverse experience of facing primal wielding psycho melees on daily basis.  A well respected pve person can suck horribly at pvp, just ask Furor and the FoH crew. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uroamereq.showPublicProfile?language=EN>roamereq</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 42<br> <font color=#333333>(12/17/01 8:33:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=69.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Hrmm...</span><hr size=1> Euriped...<br>
<br>
Quick question, have you played another class and fought againts a mage before? This is why I ask....<br>
<br>
When I started on Tallon Zek with my Mage, I started to get very disapointed once I got to the 20's range I appeared to be doing something wrong because I couldn't win a dem fight.<br>
<br>
I then created a warrior, wizard, bard, sk, and cleric within that time. Each had encountered a mage and there was 1 major thing I really learned from those encounters. The pet controlled the tempo of the battle. If it was on me continously it would spell disaster. With those classes I figured out every possible way to disable the pet so I could concentrate on the mage.<br>
<br>
Well, picking my mage back up I started to use my pet more for the fear factor rather than the damage factor. I learned that people, like me, tended to freak out and not perform up to par when that pet was constantly beating away. I took a look at my tactics in disabling a mages pet and figured out how I could prevent them from happening to my mage. <br>
<br>
By keeping the pet on the opponant, at all times, it gives me more control over the battle. Each failed attempt to disable my pet by my opponant is more time for me to analyse the battle and do as I wish.   <br>
<br>
Heading off topic... <br>
<br>
Druids: There is the cheap way to gaurantee a successful kill. Go in unbuffed (earth pet, unbuffed). <br>
<br>
1.)Spam cancel/anul magic on him to disable his buffs (sow, bye bye!).<br>
2.) Send in pet.<br>
3.) Spam lvl 8 dd.<br>
** Cancel/Anul any DOTS/snares on you or your pet. This is the lowest of all tactics, but hey. You will win **<br>
<br>
Rangers: Depending on how twinked the Ranger is and how lucky he gets, I can take them out maybe 60% of the time. You can either go Earth pet and hope for a succeful Root, then follow up with continous Mal's until 1 sticks, then DD till the cows come home. Or go fire and reverse kite (cancel/anul and snares on you FAST!).<br>
<br>
I should announce again, my experince is only from lvls 1-34, however I know many High Level mages on Tallon Zek who will vouch for me that keeping the pet on your opponant at all times is key to a glorious victory!<br>
<br>
